{"timestamp": "2025-12-05 15:28:00.926622", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting diagnosis report\nTarget network: Scalable SDN spine–leaf (topo_size small). Switches: leaf_1, leaf_2, spine_1. Hosts in subnets 10.0.0.0/24. Controller: 20.0.0.100 (OpenFlow).\n\n1) Executive summary\n- Observed complete host-to-host data-plane failure inside 10.0.0.0/24: hosts cannot ARP or ping each other (100% loss / unresolved ARP).\n- All OVS switches are configured to use an SDN controller (tcp:20.0.0.100:6633) but do not have an active OpenFlow session (controller TCP connect fails). No OpenFlow flows are installed on switches.\n- Root cause (most likely): the SDN controller is not accepting OpenFlow connections (port 6633 closed / controller process not listening), leaving switches with no flow rules. Switches use fail_mode: secure so they drop forwarding for unknown traffic -> host dataplane isolation.\n- Impact: All hosts attached to leaf switches are unable to communicate with each other (L2/L3 within 10.0.0.0/24). The control-plane (switch→controller) is down at the OpenFlow/TCP layer even though the controller's IP is reachable at ICMP.\n\n2) Symptoms observed (high level)\n- Host pings between hosts in 10.0.0.0/24 fail with \"Destination Host Unreachable\" and ARP entries are incomplete / FAILED.\n- OVS bridges report Controller \"tcp:20.0.0.100:6633\" configured but no flows returned by dump-flows.\n- Switches can ICMP-reach the controller IP, but TCP connect to controller:6633 fails.\n- Switch internal (\"LOCAL\") ports are shown as PORT_DOWN / LINK_DOWN.\n- No OpenFlow rules are present on the switches (empty flow tables).\n\n3) Key evidence (selected outputs)\n- Host-to-host ping (sample):\n  - host_1_1 -> host_1_2: \"4 packets transmitted, 0 received, +4 errors, 100% packet loss\" with \"From 10.0.0.1 icmp_seq=X Destination Host Unreachable\"\n- Host ARP/neighbor state (host_1_1):\n  - ip neigh / arp: multiple 10.0.0.x entries show \"FAILED\" / \"(incomplete)\".\n- OVS configuration (leaf_1, leaf_2, spine_1):\n  - ovs-vsctl shows Controller \"tcp:20.0.0.100:6633\" and fail_mode: secure.\n  - ovs-ofctl dump-flows returned no flows (NXST_FLOW reply empty).\n  - Bridge ports (eth0..ethn) show link/up physical speeds (10Gb-FD) but the LOCAL port is reported as PORT_DOWN / LINK_DOWN.\n- Switch -> controller connectivity checks:\n  - leaf_1 / leaf_2 / spine_1: ping 20.0.0.100 -> success (ICMP replies, ~0.8–1.0 ms).\n  - leaf_1 / leaf_2 / spine_1: curl/tcp connect to tcp://20.0.0.100:6633 -> \"tcp connect failed\".\n- Host -> controller checks:\n  - host_1_1 / host_2_1: ping 20.0.0.100 -> \"Network is unreachable\" (hosts have no route to management 20.0.0.0/24; expected given topology).\n\n4) Device localization (which components are faulty / implicated)\n- SDN Controller (20.0.0.100): suspected faulty/unavailable for OpenFlow (port 6633). Evidence: switches can ICMP the IP but unable to establish TCP on 6633.\n- OVS switches (leaf_1, leaf_2, spine_1): operational at the datapath hardware level (ports show link up) but have no OpenFlow session and no flows installed. With fail_mode=secure and no flows, they drop unknown traffic → causing host connectivity failure.\n- Hosts (host_1_1, host_1_2, host_2_1, host_2_2, etc.): appear configured correctly with expected 10.0.0.x addresses and local routes but cannot ARP reach one another because traffic is not forwarded by switches.\n\n5) Likely root cause(s) and reasoning\nPrimary root cause (most probable):\n- Controller not accepting OpenFlow connections (service down, listening on different port, firewall filtering, or misconfiguration of controller OpenFlow port). Reason:\n  - Switches show controller configured but attempts to open TCP on 20.0.0.100:6633 from switches fail (\"tcp connect failed\").\n  - ICMP to 20.0.0.100 works, so IP-level connectivity exists and the failure is at TCP port / application level.\nResulting effect:\n- No OpenFlow session → no flows installed (ovs-ofctl dump-flows empty).\n- Switches are in fail_mode: secure → they will not flood/forward unknown packets without controller-installed flows → ARP and host L2/L3 traffic dropped → hosts cannot reach each other.\n\nPossible secondary/related observations:\n- LOCAL port state = PORT_DOWN / LINK_DOWN on each OVS bridge. This is likely the internal OVS interface status and may be a side-effect of no controller rules or simply expected in this environment; however, it supports that the bridges do not have flow rules and are not forwarding host traffic.\n- Host inability to reach 20.0.0.100 is expected because hosts are on 10.0.0.0/24 while controller is on 20.0.0.0/24; unless the test path is routed via switches, hosts won't reach controller (management network is separate).\n\n6) Components/services impacted\n- All hosts attached to leaf switches: L2/L3 connectivity within the 10.0.0.0/24 is impaired.\n- OVS dataplanes: forwarding disabled for unknown flows due to missing controller.\n- SDN controller service: OpenFlow endpoint unavailable, preventing network control-plane operation.\n\n7) Confidence and next data points to collect (no mitigation)\nConfidence: high that controller OpenFlow endpoint is the immediate cause of no flows and host connectivity loss (evidence: TCP connect fails while ICMP succeeds; no flows on switches; fail_mode secure). Root cause of why controller port is closed (controller process down, listening on another port, firewall, or network policy) requires checking the controller host.\n\nRecommended additional diagnostics to confirm root cause (if you want me to run them):\n- On controller host (20.0.0.100): check OpenFlow controller process status, listen ports (ss -ltnp | grep 6633 or 6653), controller logs.\n- From a switch host (leaf_1): attempt telnet 20.0.0.100 6633 to confirm TCP-level refusal and capture TCP RST vs timeout.\n- On switches: show ovsdb/ovs logs to see controller connection attempts and reason for connection refusal.\n- On switches: ovs-ofctl show and ovs-ofctl dump-ports-desc to verify port operational state; also check ovs-vswitchd logs for OpenFlow errors.\n- Verify controller configuration: whether it should be listening on 6633 or 6653 (some controllers use 6653 by default).\n- Confirm that fail_mode is intended to be secure (observed secure) — if so, this explains drops when controller absent.\n\n8) Summary statement\nHosts are isolated because the OVS switches have no active OpenFlow control session and have no forwarding flows installed. The switches can reach the controller IP at the IP layer (ICMP), but TCP to the controller’s configured OpenFlow port (6633) fails, strongly indicating the controller is not accepting OpenFlow connections. This controller unavailability is the immediate root cause of the observed host-to-host connectivity failure.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 10931, "output_tokens": 3025, "total_tokens": 13956, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 0}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 1344}}}
